    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-04-25T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-04-25T07:00:00-05:00" n="434"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d434">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/4366: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-04-25T20:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 25, 1922—8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 18—5:51 a.m.]<note n="26" xml:id="d434fn26">This telegram
                            bears the annotation: “Repeated, delayed by radio.”</note>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>170. I have telegraphed to consuls throughout China to ascertain if any
                    anti-foreign sentiment has developed. Replies all negative except Kalgan,
                    Harbin, Canton. In Harbin cause local not national. At Canton consul had a
                    report from missionaries and commercial men in Delta that anti-foreign feeling
                    existed but could not give a concrete example. No indication Peking anti-foreign
                    agitation apart from anti-Christian agitation which regarded less as
                    anti-foreign outbreak than as reassertion of Chinese civilization versus
                    occidental with intoxication of radical scholars and scientists some of them
                    half-baked with ferment of western methods of investigation and criticism.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
